<br />
CCG&#39;s were all the rage at one point. They simply aren&#39;t anymore. Magic is the only good game left, the others have pretty much died. The kiddie games like Yu Gi Oh are still around but nothing like they used to be.<br />
<br />
Magic will always be good, everything else will be an also ran. Unless someone figures out a way to start Star Wars ccg all over again from scratch using the same system but fixing all the mistakes of the first game, I can&#39;t see any ccg doing well ever again. They would have to reinvent the wheel and even if they do, there are still way to many distractions. Video games and the internet have more or less killed ccgs. That big spike in technology in the 90&#39;s while ccgs were hot more or less killed the ccg market.<br />
<br />
Miniatures also helped kill card games a bit.<br />
<br />
I loved Magic, swccg, and LOTR, it was a lot of fun while it lasted.<br />
<br />
At this point, the only thing I like is War at Sea because World War II is something I&#39;ve always been interested in, the history of it. I also like A&A mini&#39;s but not near as much as War at Sea. WOTC took a giant dump on their army game by releasing a version 2.0 where the vehicles are larger than the original and they game them some new values and stats. Jeeez<br />
<br />
Chalk up another in a long line of clusterfocks in the gaming market.<br />
<br />
Most games just have no staying power. Stargate? Come on. Cool movie and I guess the show is ok but who does that reach? A very small market and fan base. It&#39;s not Star Trek and that focker failed too. It isn&#39;t Star Wars but look where that&#39;s at despite the great efforts of the PC(no disrespect intended, I would play if there were packs to open)and WOTC&#39;s game was total assinahat.<br />
<br />
