<br />
You missed out :( <br><BR><font size=1>10:24 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>Asphalizo</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">So the conclusion for most people that I&#39;ve seen on here is the the CCG market is on its way out.  I don&#39;t think thats true.  Yeah, things are going downhill but that doesn&#39;t necessarily mean things are finished.  Maybe the market needs to hit a low point to open peoples eyes.  From my perspective the market has been flooded with a bunch of "get rich quick TCGs" or "cash in on a franchise TCGs" lately. I don&#39;t see Magic dying in 4 years, because even if it did I think it would easily go the way of SWCCG.  I just recently started Magic in order to get a friend to sell his SW cards, but I can see the fun in the game.  The addition of the new planeswalkers and clash ability throw a new strategic aspect that will need quite a while to show their true impact.<br />
<br />
I think the aspect of a one-on-one matchup between two persons and two decks of cards is something that is still coveted by a lot of people.  Just look at poker.  Online play has boosted the market largely over the past 4 or 5 years, but isn&#39;t playing with a group around a table a lot more fun.  The physicality of the game creates the excitement.  The same goes with card games.  I played LOTR online during the beta testing and loved it, however when the game went live I dropped it.  The game had no value.  I didn&#39;t make any friends or enemies.  I played a game by myself and my computer.  That can&#39;t be duplicated right now online.  <br />
<br />
Even with SWCCG most of the time the relationships we create online don&#39;t solidify until we meet and interact with the person at big events like worlds or such.  Thus the reason I don&#39;t play on gEngine. I have friends in town to SWCCG.  The interesting things is that so-called children&#39;s card games realize this more than the more "advanced games".  Look at games like Yu-Gi-Oh which spawned a TV series.  The whole TV series is based on the relationships the main character made thru the card game.<br />
<br />
I don&#39;t think card games are on their way out. I just think that they are at a low spot before a climb begins. <br><BR><font size=1>10:09 11-01-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>CategoryOneGame</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">3rd Stargate set is going to be online only from what I have heard.  The last set was actually pushed back twice on the release date (Comic Images? or was it because of Events and wanting to have it at a Con two weeks before release so they could get the full profit off of it?)<br />
