The problem with GenCon for these companies is that I think they drop huge coin to be there...and most of the crowd is there to just try stuff out. Plus I constantly will have someone demo the game who barely knows it...the guy showing me 24 was awful. No recognition that I knew TCGs. They should immediately sieze that chance and show the full depth of the game. I walked away saying - heh, it&#39;s a JAG (just another game). <br><BR><font size=1>13:52 10-30-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#A2B1C1>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#A2B1C1><font class="bfont"><B>CategoryOneGame</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#A2B1C1' ><font class="bfont">I just read a review of Gen Con talking about how it contained more Video/Computer gaming than any years past event and that Gen Con activelly searched these companies out this year.  They mentioned that besides the D&D version 4.0 system that there weren&#39;t that many huge announcements.<br />
<br />
From what I&#39;ve heard on the Card Game side is that besides 24, everything was crap and even the 24 could be included in that depending if your a fan of the show or not.  <br />
<br />
Basically it sounds that even RPG ers are switching more to the video game side and that this event will just turn more into an E3 type event with some card game/RPG/Mini&#39;s there too.  I don&#39;t think that physical gaming is going to stick around much longer.<br />
<br />
Look at the DS thread where we now have VS and FMA on DS.  It cost me 30 bucks and I don&#39;t have to pay money again and I have hours of play.  30 bucks doesn&#39;t even buy you one box of the new set.  Yeah you don&#39;t get the wonderfull smell of the UD VS cards but you don&#39;t pay anything else.<br />
